It looks like you're trying to use ES6 `export` syntax, which is not supported in all JavaScript environments. If you're running your code in a browser that doesn't support ES6 modules, you'll need to use a different syntax for exporting your class.

One option is to use CommonJS-style exports instead:

```
class uiHelpers {
  // ...
}

module.exports = uiHelpers;
```

Then, in your other file, you can import it like this:

```
const uiHelpers = require('./ui-helpers');
```

If you want to use the newer syntax, you can either run your code through a bundler like Webpack or Babel, or you can change your script type to "module" and use the newer syntax directly in your HTML file:

```
<script type="module">
  import { uiHelpers } from './ui-helpers.js';
  // ...
</script>
```
